<tr><td align="left" valign="bottom" width="98%"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/toptab.gif" width="98" height="10" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0"></td><td align="left" valign="bottom" width="22">&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td bgcolor="#3F403F" width="98%" class="cheader"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></td><td bgcolor="3F403F" valign="top" align="right" width="22"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/topcorner.gif" width="23" height="22" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0" align="right"></td></tr>
<tr><td width="98%" colspan=2><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" class="cbody">
<tr><td><font class="h1font"> Top 10  Unwritten Rules<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.85)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=9001'>Chris "Darth Crith" Menzel</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=9001&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> September 19, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> <br />
I am often asked to help with how to compare with the top players and how to improve one’s gameplay. Since I came from being the super scrub to being an halfway decent player now,I always try to help those players that have good ideas but always walk into the same traps.<br />
This is not for you top guys out there (so please rate gently) but for the new, the bad and the ugly (which are the poor guys that are not bad but always loose anyway). <br />
It is by no way all compassing but should help as an additional guide for unwritten rules. These are sorted vaguely by turn phase to make it easier. Here goes...<br />
<br />
<br />
1. Have enough Force for you and none for your opponent<br />
<br />
Be sure that your deck gives you enough Force to do what you have to, and maybe also to pay those 3 Force extra per drain (because of Battle Plan/Order), and the 2 Force more you have to pay per character (because of Goo Nee Tay/Bad Feeling Have I).<br />
Also, give your opponent a lot less Force than yourself, especially early on. You have to be aware of the (living) Force of you and your opponent at all times. He just can’t beat you down on turn 2 at Kessel with the Executor, if he only activates 3 Force a turn.<br />
<br />
<br />
2. Search first... activate then<br />
<br />
Especially when you are the DS player and your first action is to search with Mob Points (a Defensive Shield will prevent this, if you activate 1 first). Activate 3 Force, search with Signal/Twilik Advisor for an Effect, and then activate the rest. Things like that.<br />
<br />
<br />
3. Keep your Drains alive<br />
<br />
If you rely on heavy Drains, make sure that they cannot be cancelled (like in a Walker deck).<br />
Menace Fades and Imperial Decree will still cancel your Force Drain bonuses, even if your drains cannot be cancelled. Be aware of this. And finally, even if your Drains AND the bonuses cannot be cancelled, your opponent may still play cards that prevent you from draining at all (Undercover Spies), at certain locations (like Come Here You Big Coward), and cards that prevent their Force Loss of more than 2 Force (Ultimatum/Resistance).<br />
Read all the cards named here and make sure you can handle them.<br />
<br />
<br />
4. Secure your big Drains at exterior planet sites<br />
<br />
If you drain at an exterior site, your opponent can make your characters go missing with Always Thinking With Your Stomach/Lost In The Wilderness. You can prevent this by having a vehicle/starship there or draining at mobile sites, or at interior sites.<br />
<br />
<br />
5. Search for free and only then for sure<br />
<br />
Deploy that Docking Bay (DB) or whatever for free from Reserve Deck and while doing so look through your Deck. Make sure everything else you want to take from the Deck is in there (especially if you can deploy it only once per game). Matching ships or weapons for characters you have in hand, Effects, cards you can deploy from objective, etc. <br />
Also, look if ALL of your key cards (that one Effect you absolutely need) or their helpers (the 2 Signals you packed to get it early) are in there. If not (and you have no Used Pile), you may want to draw everything at the end of the turn. They must be in your Force then.<br />
<br />
<br />
6. Secure your 2 Ability characters at interior sites<br />
<br />
If you have that Enraged Chewie with Han, Leia and Lando at the Cantina and the only card in your hand is Life Debt, you can (and WILL) still get beaten there by Dengar with Gun, Dr. Evazan/Ponda Baba and this un-pronouncable 8-power alien. Blast The Door Kid/Stunning Leader) is the card that often makes the difference, as it excludes all characters above 2 ability and all leaders from battle. <br />
In the above example, your Chewie would get shot to forfeit 0, you would draw no destiny, and loose 7-17 Force in ADDITION (counting a possible 10 Destiny against Senate). And you might have seen your opponents hand, and thought it was no big deal.<br />
<br />
<br />
7. Don’t leave cannon fodder alive<br />
<br />
It is in general a very bad idea to leave your small character, that does not draw a Destiny itself, alone or with your big guy. The big one might become excluded (Clash Of Sabers, Dr E Combo, etc.), and you are very kicked then.<br />
If you have to loose either Han or Chewie after a battle with only these two, and next turn is your opponent’s turn (and he has lots of Force and hand cards), try to forfeit BOTH. I drew a 7 and Han has Forfeit 7 and Chewie Forfeit 6. Forfeit Chewie, and then Han for 1 left. <br />
Or try to get rid of your own guy by not paying Maintenance cost instead of getting clobbered next turn. Suicide can be creative and often helps. Just don’t quote me on the last sentence anywhere. <br />
<br />
<br />
8. Keep extra Force for the Battle<br />
<br />
A card like Projective Telepathy (DS only) will force you to use 2 extra for a battle or drain and Draw Their Fire (LS) will force you to use 1 Force per Interrupt during battles. Just something to keep in mind.<br />
<br />
<br />
9. Keep your hand at 12 Cards<br />
<br />
You probably know that Grimtaash/Monnok can force you to EITHER place all cards over 12 randomly in Used Pile OR (if played lost) force you to discard all doubles. Also know, that both these Interrupts (at least the Combo Cards) can be taken from Reserve Deck with Effects like Crush The Rebellion EVERY TURN. <br />
And for the doubles, the unique characters are also strongly hindered by Abyss/Chasm, when you have an exact same copy on table (destiny +2 Force lost for you).<br />
<br />
<br />
10. Stop deploying and drawing, Dammit!<br />
<br />
Don’t deploy 3 characters, and wonder 2 turns later why you lost a Drain race game with 3 Force. The same goes for drawing and drawing, although you win anyway. Or keeping the Executor and Chimera in hand and loose the top card of your Reserve Deck, leaving only 8 cards to deploy neither card anymore. It all adds up to keep count of how many cards you have in your Life Force (what you need to deploy something) and Hand (where you deploy from). <br />
This is especially important in the later game turns. Make it a habit to start thinking very strong about these things when you reach around 15 Force (if you need a number).<br />
<br />
 <br />
<br />
So, that’s it for now. Many things are left unsaid of course. Tracking, paying any cost without your opponent reminding you to do so first, deck construction, card knownledge, and so on. That is all stuff where you will find excellent articles on Decktech (and elsewhere). But the above happen almost every game, and cannot be stressed enough. When you hear the alarm bells when seeing an exterior or interior site, and when you don’t draw cards to lower your own differential when winning, THEN I have reached my goal. <br />
Also, it is a ton to learn and have in mind, and you will be a much better player when you keep to these 10 points. Go back and read the article AFTER a bad tourney. You will find familiar stuff guaranteed. Soon you will use the abusive cards yourself.<br />
Just one last thing... you will be slower first, when trying to remember everything and evaluating the whole situation. When you reach time out, and a better player JUST would not win because you were slow... be a gentleman and draw up. Your day will come!<br />
<br />
May the Force be with you<br />
<br />
Darth Crith (Shadow 14)<br />
